## Setup steps

### 1. Complete the small-team setup first

Provision the hub, create the least-privilege role (`mtix_sync`),
run `mtix sync init`, confirm baseline `push / pull` works on every
machine. Confirm `.mtix/secrets` is mode 0600 on every machine
(`mtix sync doctor` reports this).

### 2. Run the daemon as a service on every developer machine

Un-pushed events are NOT durable across machine loss. Compliance
profiles typically cannot tolerate that risk; the daemon is the
mitigation.

```bash
mtix sync daemon --install | sudo tee /etc/systemd/system/mtix-sync.service
sudo systemctl enable --now mtix-sync
```

The daemon runs `mtix sync pull` every 30 seconds by default and is
also where periodic auto-push can be wired (the daemon's pull pass
will surface new events from teammates; a separate cron / timer
running `mtix sync push` covers the outbound direction).

Document in your team runbook: developers MUST verify
`systemctl status mtix-sync` shows `active (running)` before logging
off each day.

### 3. Schedule hub backups to immutable cold storage

`mtix sync backup --output FILE` wraps `pg_dump` for the 5
mtix-owned tables (`sync_events`, `sync_conflicts`, `sync_projects`,
`applied_events`, `audit_log`) with `--no-owner --no-privileges` for
portability.

Schedule a daily backup to immutable cold storage:

```bash
# In a cron / systemd timer on a hardened operator machine:
DATE=$(date -u +%Y%m%dT%H%M%SZ)
mtix sync backup --output "/tmp/mtix-hub-${DATE}.sql"
aws s3 cp "/tmp/mtix-hub-${DATE}.sql" \
  "s3://my-compliance-bucket/mtix-hub/${DATE}.sql" \
  --acl bucket-owner-full-control
shred -u "/tmp/mtix-hub-${DATE}.sql"
```

Configure the destination bucket with Object Lock (S3) or equivalent
retention policy (GCS, Azure Blob Immutable Storage). The backup is
the canonical record of what the hub saw; the audit_log triggers
prevent mutation in-place, but they do not prevent a PG superuser
from disabling the triggers — only the external archive does.

### 4. Confirm append-only invariants

As a non-superuser, verify the triggers raise on UPDATE/DELETE:

```sql
UPDATE audit_log SET ... WHERE id = 1;
-- expected: ERROR:  audit_log is append-only

DELETE FROM sync_conflicts WHERE id = 1;
-- expected: ERROR:  sync_conflicts is append-only
```

Document the result in your compliance evidence.

### 5. Server-side enforcement of pre-push sync

Pick the variant that matches your hosting:

- **Self-hosted git (GitLab, Gitea, raw git):** install
  `examples/hooks/pre-receive` on the server. The hook verifies the
  developer pushed events by comparing the local pending queue
  signature against the hub.
- **GitHub.com:** add the snapshot-check job to
  `.github/workflows/` and add a branch protection rule requiring
  it.

This prevents `git push --no-verify` from bypassing the local
`pre-push` hook.

### 6. Consider distinct authorIDs per agent

If your audit requirements include hub-side traceability of every
contested edit (not just the LWW-resolved outcome), set distinct
`authorID` values per agent process. Two CLIs that share
`authorID="cli"` produce vector clocks that are `Equal()` rather
than `Concurrent()`; same-authorID concurrent edits are resolved by
LWW but do NOT produce a `sync_conflicts` row on the hub.

This is the audit-trail tradeoff documented in
[docs/SECURITY-MODEL.md](../SECURITY-MODEL.md#known-audit-trail-limitation-same-authorid-conflicts).
For safety-critical adopters, the runbook recommendation is to
configure each CI runner / agent with a distinct authorID so that
all contested edits land in `sync_conflicts`.

(The CLI does not yet expose a flag to override the authorID; until
it does, the workaround is to set it via direct meta UPDATE during
agent bootstrap.)

### 7. Rehearse the DR procedure

See the [Disaster recovery](#disaster-recovery) section below. Run
the drill at least quarterly and record the elapsed restore time.

### 8. Train the team

Every team member must read
[docs/SECURITY-MODEL.md](../SECURITY-MODEL.md) and acknowledge the
trust assumptions. mtix does not enforce per-user data isolation
within a single hub instance.

